diagnoses.name: Measles
diagnoses.description: A highly infectious viral illness known to cause fever, cough, conjunctivitis, and a characteristic rash.

diagnoses.name: Kawasaki disease
diagnoses.description: A condition that causes inflammation in the walls of some blood vessels in the body. It's most often seen in children. Symptoms include fever, rash, swelling of the hands and feet, irritation and redness of the eyes, and red, dry, or cracked lips.

diagnoses.name: Scarlet fever
diagnoses.description: A bacterial illness that develops in some people who have strep throat. It features a bright red rash that covers most of the body, sore throat, and high fever.

diagnoses.name: Stevens-Johnson syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, serious disorder of the skin and mucous membranes. It's usually a reaction to a medication or an infection. Often, it begins with flu-like symptoms, followed by a painful red or purplish rash that spreads and blisters.

diagnoses.name: Toxic Epidermal Necrolysis
diagnoses.description: A severe skin condition that causes widespread reddening of the skin and blisters, leading to the top layer of the skin to die and shed. It's often induced by a reaction to drugs.

diagnoses.name: Infectious mononucleosis
diagnoses.description: An infection with the Epstein-Barr virus. It's characterized by fatigue, fever, rash, and leukocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Rubella
diagnoses.description: Also known as German measles or three-day measles, rubella is a contagious viral infection best known by its distinctive red rash.

diagnoses.name: Drug Reaction with Eosinophilia and Systemic Symptoms (DRESS) Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A drug reaction that includes symptoms such as rash, fever, lymphadenopathy, and eosinophilia. It can also affect various organs, such as the liver, kidneys, and lungs.

diagnoses.name: Adenovirus infection
diagnoses.description: An infection caused by adenovirus that can lead to symptoms ranging from cold-like symptoms to conjunctivitis and, in some severe cases, to an illness that affects the entire body.

diagnoses.name: Erythema infectiosum
diagnoses.description: A viral infection that most commonly affects children and causes a facial rash (often referred to as slapped cheek disease), fever, and a rash on the body.

diagnoses.name: Measles
diagnoses.description: A highly contagious viral infection causing fever, cough, and characteristic spots. Measles can lead to severe complications including pneumonia and encephalitis.

diagnoses.name: Erythema infectiosum (Fifth disease)
diagnoses.description: A viral infection caused by Parvovirus B19, presenting with mild flu-like symptoms followed by a distinctive facial rash (slapped cheek appearance) and a lace-like rash on the body.

diagnoses.name: Dengue Fever
diagnoses.description: A mosquito-borne viral illness common in tropical and subtropical areas, characterized by fever, severe headache, pain behind the eyes, joint and muscle pain, rash, and mild bleeding.

diagnoses.name: Zika Virus Infection
diagnoses.description: Primarily spread through mosquito bites, this viral infection is known for mild symptoms such as fever, rash, conjunctivitis, and joint pain. It is of particular concern in pregnant women due to its association with birth defects.

diagnoses.name: Rubella (German measles)
diagnoses.description: A contagious viral infection preventable by vaccine and known for its distinctive red rash. It is mild in children but can cause serious birth defects if contracted by pregnant women.

diagnoses.name: Scarlet Fever
diagnoses.description: An infection that can develop in people who have strep throat, characterized by a bright red rash that covers most of the body, fever, and a sore throat.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatic Fever
diagnoses.description: A disease that can develop after a strep throat or scarlet fever infection, characterized by inflammatory lesions. It can affect the heart, joints, skin, and brain.

diagnoses.name: Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV)
diagnoses.description: HIV infection can present with a variety of symptoms including a maculopapular rash, fever, lymphadenopathy, and in later stages, significant immunosuppression leading to opportunistic infections.

diagnoses.name: Leptospirosis
diagnoses.description: A bacterial disease that affects humans and animals. Symptoms can range from none to severe and include high fever, headache, bleeding, muscle pain, chills, red eyes, and jaundice.

diagnoses.name: Kawasaki Disease
diagnoses.description: A condition that causes inflammation in the walls of some blood vessels in the body. It's mostly seen in children. The symptoms include fever, rash, swelling of the hands and feet, red eyes, and redness of the mouth, lips, and throat.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can affect multiple systems including the skin, kidneys, and joints. Presents with a characteristic butterfly rash, systemic symptoms, and can include nephritis and synovitis.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease marked by muscle weakness and a distinctive skin rash, can also involve internal organs like the kidneys.

diagnoses.name: Psoriatic Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory arthritis associated with psoriasis. It can produce a rash as well as affect the joints (synovitis) and kidneys.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory disorder affecting many joints, including those in the hands and feet. While arthritis is the hallmark, systemic features can include skin manifestations and renal involvement.

diagnoses.name: Henoch-Schönlein Purpura (HSP)
diagnoses.description: A disease causing inflammation and bleeding in the small blood vessels in your skin, joints, intestines, and kidneys. Skin presentation includes a rash, often palpable and can be mistaken for a more generic maculopapular rash in early stages.

diagnoses.name: Syphilis
diagnoses.description: A sexually transmitted infection that can present with a variety of symptoms depending on the stage of the infection. Secondary syphilis can include a maculopapular rash and alopecia. Tertiary syphilis can involve the kidneys.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: Human immunodeficiency virus causes progressive failure of the immune system leading to opportunistic infections and malignancies. Skin rashes and kidney diseases such as HIV-associated nephropathy can occur.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: Caused by the bacterium Borrelia burgdorferi transmitted to humans through the bite of infected blacklegged ticks. Early dissemination can cause a variety of symptoms, including rashes (often erythema migrans, but can present atypically), and more systemic issues in late stages.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.description: A rare autoimmune disorder that has features common to lupus, scleroderma, and polymyositis including skin rashes, joint pain, and renal involvement.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that affects multiple organs in the body, but mostly the lungs and lymph glands. Skin manifestations (like lupus pernio), and renal involvement are also common.

Diabetes Mellitus – Hyperglycemia is a classic symptom of diabetes.
Sarcoidosis – This condition can explain lymphadenopathy, eye irritation (uveitis), and skin manifestations that might contribute to pruritus. Bone pain could result from granulomatous lesions.
Hodgkin's Lymphoma – Symptoms include pain following alcohol consumption, lymphadenopathy, pruritus, and systemic symptoms like weight loss or fever.
Non-Hodgkin's Lymphoma – Similar to Hodgkin's lymphoma, it can present with lymphadenopathy, bone pain, and systemic symptoms.
Leukemia – Chronic or acute forms can present with bone pain, lymphadenopathy, and systemic symptoms including eye manifestations.
Hyperparathyroidism – Can cause bone pain due to high calcium levels and might indirectly cause hyperglycemia and other systemic symptoms.
Multiple Myeloma – Characterized by bone pain, hypercalcemia (which can cause polyuria, contributing to hyperglycemia), and systemic symptoms.
HIV/AIDS – Can present with generalized lymphadenopathy, various dermatologic manifestations including pruritus, eye problems, and systemic symptoms.
Lymphoma – Both Hodgkin's and non-Hodgkin's lymphoma can cause lymphadenopathy, bone pain, and systemic symptoms.

Chronic Kidney Disease – Can cause hyperglycemia, pruritus (due to uremic pruritus), bone pain (due to secondary hyperparathyroidism or renal osteodystrophy), and possibly eye irritation due to secondary complications.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Granulomatous Disease
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder that affects the immune system, leading to frequent infections, including otitis media. It can also impact growth and development, potentially contributing to delayed puberty. Abnormal liver enzymes may indicate liver involvement due to recurrent infections.

diagnoses.name: Primary Immunodeficiency Disorders
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders causing impaired immune system function. Patients often present with recurrent ear infections (otitis media), may have growth and developmental delays (including delayed puberty), and can experience frequent infections leading to liver enzyme abnormalities.

diagnoses.name: Celiac Disease
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder where ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine. It can cause delayed puberty due to malabsorption of nutrients, and may be associated with liver enzyme abnormalities. Otitis media and frequent waking could be less directly related symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Non-alcoholic Fatty Liver Disease (NAFLD)
diagnoses.description: A range of liver conditions affecting people who drink little to no alcohol. It shows as abnormal liver enzymes. While not directly causing otitis media or delayed puberty, underlying metabolic syndrome could influence growth and development.

diagnoses.name: Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD)
diagnoses.description: A chronic digestive disease where stomach acid or bile irritates the food pipe lining. It's linked with symptoms like post-nasal drip. Abnormal liver enzymes, frequent waking, and less commonly, otitis media, could be related due to associated conditions.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition where the thyroid gland is underactive. It can cause delayed puberty due to hormonal imbalances, and mediate abnormal liver enzymes. Patients might experience frequent waking and, less typically, otitis media.

diagnoses.name: Turner Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A chromosomal disorder affecting females, where one of the X chromosomes is missing or partially missing. It often results in delayed puberty. While otitis media is not a hallmark, individuals may experience it alongside abnormal liver enzymes.

diagnoses.name: Klinefelter Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A genetic condition affecting males, who have an extra X chromosome. Symptoms include delayed puberty. While otitis media and abnormal liver enzymes are less common, associated endocrine dysfunctions could indirectly contribute to these findings.

diagnoses.name: Alpha-1 Antitrypsin Deficiency
diagnoses.description: A genetic condition leading to lung and liver disease. It can result in abnormal liver enzymes and, in children, can contribute to recurrent respiratory infections like otitis media. Delayed puberty could be a less direct symptom related to overall health.

diagnoses.name: Wilson Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare inherited disorder that causes copper to accumulate in the liver, brain, and other vital organs. It presents with abnormal liver enzymes and can lead to symptoms affecting various systems, although direct connections to otitis media or delayed puberty are less clear.

diagnoses.reasoning: Your combination of symptoms includes obsessive-compulsive behavior, which directly relates to OCD. Other symptoms could be secondary or go along with the stress associated with OCD.

Anxiety can manifest in various physical symptoms, including laryngitis (due to stress and strain on the vocal cords), blood pressure lability, and difficulty focusing vision. The obsessive-compulsive behavior could be a part of or a response to underlying anxiety.

Blood pressure lability points towards issues with blood pressure regulation, indicating possible hypertension. While difficulty focusing vision can be a symptom, obsessive-compulsive behavior could accompany chronic stress and the stress of dealing with a chronic condition.

Symptoms like blood pressure lability, difficulty focusing, and even changes in behavior or mood can be linked to hyperthyroidism. Excessive thyroid hormone production can lead to neuropsychiatric symptoms and various systemic symptoms.
Directly related to the symptom of laryngitis. Other symptoms like difficulty focusing could stem from the general distress and discomfort of dealing with a chronic voice disorder.

Chronic stress can result in a wide range of physical and psychological symptoms, including those listed. It can directly cause or exacerbate existing issues like blood pressure lability and obsessive-compulsive behaviors.

Depression can manifest physically and may be the underlying cause of specified symptoms. Obsessive-compulsive behavior may also appear in depressive contexts, as can fluctuations in blood pressure and concentration issues.
This group of disorders pertains to the autonomic nervous system, which controls blood pressure, among other functions. Symptoms can include lability of blood pressure and difficulty focusing vision.

While primarily associated with difficulty focusing vision, the stress and discomfort of untreated visual issues can indirectly contribute to symptoms like blood pressure lability and increase stress, potentially aggravating obsessive-compulsive behaviors.
Similar to chronic stress, acute stress disorder can result in a vast array of symptoms, potentially explaining the entirety of the symptom profile as a response to a significant stressor.

diagnoses: Thyrotoxicosis without thyrotoxic crisis or storm

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which your thyroid gland doesn't produce enough of certain crucial hormones. Hypothyroidism may not cause noticeable symptoms in the early stages, but over time, untreated hypothyroidism can cause a number of health problems, such as obesity, joint pain, infertility, and heart disease.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin deficiency
diagnoses.description: Lack of sufficient vitamins can lead to various health issues, including gum problems that might cause oral pain, skin conditions such as dermatographism, and systemic issues that could contribute to weight gain.

diagnoses.name: Leukoplakia
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by white patches or plaques on the mucous membranes of the oral cavity, including the tongue. It is a potentially precancerous lesion, and in some cases, it can be associated with chronic irritation or use of tobacco products.

diagnoses.name: Oral and pharyngeal cancer
diagnoses.description: Cancer that starts in the mouth or throat. Symptoms can include oral pain and white patches inside the mouth (leukoplakia) among other signs.

diagnoses.name: Hypertension
diagnoses.description: High blood pressure can lead to epistaxis (nosebleeds) due to the increased pressure on the capillaries in the nasal passages. It is often related to obesity which can be seen in association with weight gain.

diagnoses.name: Cushing's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A condition that occurs from exposure to high cortisol levels for a long time. The syndrome can manifest in weight gain, particularly in the trunk and face, alongside a variety of other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Rhinitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the nasal mucous membrane, which can cause epistaxis. This condition might coexist with other symptoms due to a variety of factors, including environmental or allergic reactions.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.description: A metabolic disorder that can lead to weight gain. Poorly controlled diabetes can also make individuals more susceptible to infections, which could potentially explain oral pain.

diagnoses.name: Polycythemia Vera
diagnoses.description: A type of blood cancer that causes the bone marrow to produce too many red blood cells. These excess cells thicken the blood, slowing its flow, which can lead to complications such as epistaxis.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: This is a rare genetic condition that can cause episodes of swelling in various parts of the body, including the skin (potentially explaining dermatographism). Weight gain is not a direct symptom but could be indirectly related due to treatment or lifestyle.

diagnoses: Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder (Secondary to Stress or Chronic Illness)

diagnoses.name: Asthma
diagnoses.description: Asthma is a condition in which your airways narrow and swell and may produce extra mucus. This can make breathing difficult and trigger coughing, wheezing, and shortness of breath.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Hemorrhagic Telangiectasia (HHT)
diagnoses.description: HHT is a genetic disorder that affects blood vessels and can cause bleeding and the formation of telangiectasias, particularly in the skin, mucous membranes, lungs, and brain.

diagnoses.name: Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)
diagnoses.description: PCOS is a hormonal disorder common among women of reproductive age. Women with PCOS may have infrequent or prolonged menstrual periods or excess male hormone (androgen) levels. The ovaries may develop numerous small collections of fluid (follicles) and fail to regularly release eggs.

diagnoses.name: Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome (EDS)
diagnoses.description: EDS is a group of disorders that affect connective tissues supporting the skin, bones, blood vessels, and many other organs and tissues. It can lead to joint pain, including back pain, and sometimes skin cysts.

diagnoses.name: Cystic Fibrosis
diagnoses.description: Cystic fibrosis affects the cells that produce mucus, sweat, and digestive juices. It causes these fluids to become thick and sticky, plugging up tubes, ducts, and passageways, potentially leading to severe respiratory and digestive problems.

diagnoses.name: Atopic Dermatitis
diagnoses.description: Atopic dermatitis is a condition that makes your skin red and itchy. It's common in children but can occur at any age. Atopic dermatitis is long-lasting (chronic) and tends to flare periodically.

diagnoses.name: Sleep Apnea
diagnoses.description: Sleep apnea is a potentially serious sleep disorder in which breathing repeatedly stops and starts. Frequent waking at night may be a sign of sleep apnea.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD)
diagnoses.description: COPD is a chronic inflammatory lung disease that causes obstructed airflow from the lungs. Symptoms include breathing difficulty, cough, mucus (sputum) production, and wheezing.

diagnoses.name: Lupus
diagnoses.description: Lupus is a systemic autoimmune disease that occurs when your body's immune system attacks your own tissues and organs. Inflammation caused by lupus can affect many different body systems — including your joints, skin, kidneys, blood cells, brain, heart, and lungs.

diagnoses.name: Renal Cysts and Diabetes Syndrome (RCAD)
diagnoses.description: RCAD is a condition that typically entails the development of renal cysts in conjunction with type 2 diabetes. It reflects a broader set of symptoms including those affecting the kidneys and potentially impacting sleep patterns due to associated pain or discomfort.

diagnoses.name: Viral Infection
diagnoses.reasoning: Common viral infections can lead to symptoms like irritability, coryza (common cold symptoms), and lymphadenopathy as the body's immune response. Abnormal electrolytes and attention deficit could result from dehydration or the body's overall reaction to the infection.

diagnoses.name: Mononucleosis
diagnoses.reasoning: Also known as 'mono', caused by the Epstein-Barr virus, presents with Lymphadenopathy, fatigue (contributing to attention deficit), fever, and possibly leading to abnormal electrolyte balances due to dehydration or liver impact.

diagnoses.name: Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia
diagnoses.reasoning: A type of cancer that affects the white blood cells and can cause Lymphadenopathy, an imbalance in electrolytes due to kidney impact or treatment effects, and irritability or attention deficit due to the overall condition of the patient.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.reasoning: HIV infection, particularly in the advanced stage as AIDS, can cause generalized Lymphadenopathy, electrolyte imbalances due to diarrheal diseases or medication side effects, and cognitive changes that might present as irritability or attention-deficit phenomena.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.reasoning: A chronic autoimmune disease that can cause widespread inflammation affecting many parts of the body, including the lymph nodes (Lymphadenopathy), brain (leading to irritability and attention deficit), and kidneys (potentially causing abnormal electrolytes).

diagnoses.name: Kawasaki Disease
diagnoses.reasoning: Primarily affects children and can cause Lymphadenopathy, changes in mood such as irritability, and can lead to abnormal electrolyte balances due to the impact on the cardiovascular system and potential dehydration.

diagnoses.name: Sjogren's Syndrome
diagnoses.reasoning: An autoimmune disorder presenting with its hallmark symptoms of dry eyes and mouth, but it can also cause Lymphadenopathy, neurological manifestations (such as attention deficit), and indirectly lead to electrolyte imbalances due to reduced fluid intake or renal involvement.

diagnoses.name: Toxoplasmosis
diagnoses.reasoning: This infection, often from cats, can cause Lymphadenopathy and affect the central nervous system, leading to irritability or attention deficit. It may also cause abnormal electrolytes if there is significant involvement of the liver or kidneys.

diagnoses.name: Post-streptococcal Glomerulonephritis
diagnoses.reasoning: Following a strep infection, this condition can lead to renal impairment, reflected in abnormal electrolytes, and swollen lymph nodes. The stress and discomfort of the condition can contribute to irritability and attention challenges.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatic Fever
diagnoses.reasoning: Following a streptococcal infection, rheumatic fever can cause Lymphadenopathy, affect the brain (leading to symptoms of irritability or attention deficit), and heart or kidney dysfunction which could contribute to electrolyte imbalances.

diagnoses.name: Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD)
diagnoses.rationale: ADHD can manifest in attention deficit, and individuals with ADHD may also display obsessive-compulsive behaviors.

diagnoses.name: Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD)
diagnoses.rationale: People with ASD may have attention deficits, physical sensitivities to stimuli, and engage in repetitive behaviors that can resemble obsessive-compulsive behaviors.

diagnoses.name: Generalized Anxiety Disorder (GAD)
diagnoses.rationale: GAD can cause obsessive-compulsive behaviors as a way of coping with anxiety, and anxiety can also exacerbate or contribute to symptoms like tinnitus and attentional difficulties.

diagnoses.name: Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder (OCD)
diagnoses.rationale: OCD is characterized by obsessive-compulsive behaviors, and it may also lead to or be associated with attentional issues.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.rationale: Fibromyalgia might explain physical sensitivities due to a heightened response to pain and pressure, and some patients report cognitive difficulties akin to attention deficits.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.rationale: Glycemic lability is a hallmark of poorly controlled diabetes, which can also indirectly cause attention deficits and physical sensitivities due to complications.

diagnoses.name: Migraine Disorders
diagnoses.rationale: Individuals with migraines might experience tinnitus and physical sensitivities as part of their aura or symptomatology, alongside cognitive effects like attention difficulties.

diagnoses.name: Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome (POTS)
diagnoses.rationale: POTS can lead to glycemic lability and physical sensitivities, as well as cognitive issues such as attention deficits due to brain fog.

diagnoses.name: Major Depressive Disorder (MDD)
diagnoses.rationale: Depression can lead to cognitive impairments such as attention deficits; some individuals might engage in obsessive-compulsive behaviors as coping mechanisms or expressions of their condition.

diagnoses.name: Thyroid Disorders (Hypothyroidism/Hyperthyroidism)
diagnoses.rationale: Thyroid imbalances can affect attention, cause physical sensitivities, and influence mental health, potentially leading to obsessive-compulsive behaviors.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes. A stroke is a medical emergency, and prompt treatment is crucial.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.description: Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a potentially disabling disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). The immune system attacks the protective sheath (myelin) that covers nerve fibers, causing communication problems between your brain and the rest of your body.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A brain tumor is a mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Many different types of brain tumors exist. Some brain tumors are noncancerous (benign), and some brain tumors are cancerous (malignant). Brain tumors can begin in your brain (primary brain tumors), or cancer can begin in other parts of your body and spread to your brain (secondary, or metastatic, brain tumors).

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a ministroke, a transient ischemic attack (TIA) is a brief period of symptoms similar to those of a stroke. A TIA usually lasts only a few minutes and doesn’t cause permanent damage.

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barre Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Guillain-Barre syndrome is a rare disorder in which your body's immune system attacks your nerves. Weakness and tingling in your extremities are usually the first symptoms. These sensations can quickly spread, eventually paralyzing your whole body.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: Migraine is a neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms. It's frequently characterized by intense, debilitating headaches. Symptoms may include nausea, vomiting, difficulty speaking, numbness or tingling, and sensitivity to light and sound.

diagnoses.name: Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS)
diagnoses.description: Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) is a neurological disease that causes muscle weakness and impacts physical function. ALS is also known as Lou Gehrig’s disease.

diagnoses.name: Myasthenia Gravis
diagnoses.description: Myasthenia gravis is characterized by weakness and rapid fatigue of any of the muscles under your voluntary control. It's caused by a breakdown in the normal communication between nerves and muscles.

diagnoses.name: Brain Abscess
diagnoses.description: A brain abscess is a collection of pus that develops in response to an infection or trauma. It is a potentially life-threatening condition that requires urgent medical treatment.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: Lyme disease is caused by four main species of bacteria. Lyme disease is transmitted by the bite of an infected black-legged tick, commonly known as a deer tick. Symptoms can include fever, headache, fatigue, and a characteristic skin rash. If left untreated, infection can spread to joints, the heart, and the nervous system.

diagnoses.details: A stroke might manifest with symptoms like dysarthria and aphasia due to brain damage. In some cases, vertigo, nausea, and sensitivity to sound might also be present.
Previously known as basilar-type migraine, it can present with vertigo, dysarthria, tinnitus, and phonophobia, along with the typical migraine headache.
Multiple sclerosis can cause dysarthria and aphasia due to demyelination in the brain, and some patients might experience vertigo and nausea as well.
Depending on its location, a brain tumor might cause dysarthria, aphasia, and even vertigo if it affects balance centers or pathways.
Is a disorder of the inner ear that can lead to vertigo, hearing loss, and tinnitus, and in some cases, nausea and phonophobia.
Often referred to as a 'mini-stroke', can manifest with symptoms similar to a stroke, like dysarthria and aphasia, but they usually resolve within 24 hours.
This condition, which results from poor blood flow in the back of the brain, can cause symptoms like vertigo, dysarthria, and double vision.
This is an inflammation of the vestibular nerve, which can cause severe vertigo and nausea, but not directly linked with dysarthria or aphasia.
Some types of focal seizures can cause aphasia and/or dysarthria temporarily. Vertigo and nausea can be part of the postictal state.
An inner ear infection that can cause vertigo, hearing loss, and nausea. While it doesn't directly cause dysarthria or aphasia, its symptoms can be debilitating.

diagnoses: Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) with CNS involvement

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A neurological condition characterized by intense headaches often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and sensitivity to light and sound.

diagnoses.name: Viral Gastroenteritis
diagnoses.description: An intestinal infection marked by watery diarrhea, abdominal cramps, nausea or vomiting, and sometimes fever.

diagnoses.name: Food Poisoning
diagnoses.description: An illness caused by eating contaminated food. Symptoms include nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea.

diagnoses.name: Concussion
diagnoses.description: A brain injury caused by a blow to the head or a violent shaking of the head and body. Symptoms can include headaches, nausea, and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the fluid and membranes surrounding your brain and spinal cord. Symptoms can include headache, fever, nausea, and stiffness of the neck.

diagnoses.name: Pregnancy
diagnoses.description: Early stages of pregnancy can cause nausea, vomiting (morning sickness), and headaches.

diagnoses.name: Dehydration
diagnoses.description: A condition caused by the excessive loss of water from the body. Symptoms can include weakness, vomiting, and headache.

diagnoses.name: Heat exhaustion
diagnoses.description: A condition whose symptoms may include heavy sweating and a rapid pulse, a result of your body overheating. Symptoms also include nausea, headache, and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Symptoms can include headaches, nausea, vomiting, and weakness, depending on the location and size of the tumor.

diagnoses.name: Hypoglycemia
diagnoses.description: A condition caused by a very low level of blood sugar (glucose), your body's main energy source. Symptoms can include headache, weakness, nausea, and vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache characterized by recurrent attacks of moderate to severe pain. The aura may include visual disturbances such as scintillation, and other symptoms like tinnitus, headache, and vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear causing episodes of spinning vertigo, hearing loss, tinnitus, and sometimes a feeling of fullness or pressure in the ear.

diagnoses.name: Vestibular migraine
diagnoses.description: A variant of migraine in which the primary symptom is dizziness, vertigo, or imbalance, often accompanied by migraine symptoms like headache, photophobia, and nausea.

diagnoses.name: Brain tumor
diagnoses.description: An abnormal growth of cells within the brain, which can cause symptoms such as headache, vomiting, seizures, and changes in vision or hearing, including tinnitus.

diagnoses.name: Idiopathic intracranial hypertension
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by high pressure in the brain without a detectable cause, leading to symptoms including headache, vision problems, nausea, and occasionally tinnitus.

diagnoses.name: Acoustic neuroma
diagnoses.description: A benign tumor on the cranial nerve that connects the inner ear with the brain. It typically causes hearing loss, tinnitus, and may also cause dizziness and balance problems.

diagnoses.name: Labyrinthitis
diagnoses.description: An inner ear infection or inflammation causing imbalance, vertigo, hearing loss, and tinnitus.

diagnoses.name: Basilar migraine
diagnoses.description: A rare form of migraine with aura symptoms originating from the brainstem or both hemispheres simultaneously, often with vertigo, tinnitus, vision changes, ataxia, and occasionally loss of consciousness.

diagnoses.name: Hypertension
diagnoses.description: High blood pressure can occasionally present with headache, vomiting, and in rare cases, tinnitus, particularly if very high or with sudden spikes.

diagnoses.name: Temporal arteritis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of blood vessels, typically in the head, that can cause headaches, jaw pain, vision problems, and sometimes symptoms like tinnitus.
